{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2018}} {{EngvarB|date=February 2018}} {{Infobox academic | honorific_prefix = | name = Andrew Walls | honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE|size=100%}} | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = Andrew F. Walls.jpg | image_size = | alt = | caption = | birth_name = <!-- Use only if different from full/othernames --> | birth_date = {{birth year and age|1928}} | birth_place = [[New Milton]], England | death_date = <!-- {{death date and age|df=y|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) --> | death_place = | death_cause = | region = | nationality = British | occupation = Scholar of [[Missiologist|missions]] and [[religious studies]] | period = | known_for = History of the African church and a pioneer in the academic field of [[World Christianity]] | title = | boards = <!-- Board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation --> | spouse = Doreen (née Harden), Ingrid (née Reneau) | children = | awards = <!--Notable national level awards only--> | signature = | signature_size = | signature_alt = | education = | alma_mater = [[Exeter College, Oxford]] | thesis_title = | thesis_url = | thesis_year = | doctoral_advisor =[[Frank Leslie Cross]] | influences = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source--> | era = | discipline = [[Missiology]], [[religious studies]] | sub_discipline = <!-- Academic discipline specialist area - e.g. Sub-atomic research, 20th Century Danish specialist, Pauline research, Arcadian and Ugaritic specialist --> | workplaces = [[Fourah Bay College]], [[University of Edinburgh]], [[Liverpool Hope University]] | doctoral_students = | notable_students = <!--Only those with WP articles--> | main_interests = | notable_works = | notable_ideas = | influenced = <!--Must be referenced from a third party source--> | website = | footnotes = | movement = <!-- Should match the ideological movement or denomination (for religious), "school" of thought etc. (e.g. "Anglican", "Postmodernist", "Socialist" or "Green" etc. --> }} '''Andrew Finlay Walls''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OBE}} (born 1928) is a British historian of [[Missiology|missions]], best known for his pioneering studies of the history of the African church and a pioneer in the academic field of [[World Christianity]].<ref>{{cite book|editor-last1=Burrows |editor-first1=William R.|editor-last2=Gornik |editor-first2=Mark R. |editor-last3=McLean |editor-first3=Janice A.|title=Understanding World Christianity: The Vision and Work of Andrew F. Walls |location=Maryknoll, NY|publisher=Orbis Books |date=2011}}</ref>
==Biography== Walls was born in 1928 in [[New Milton]], England. He studied theology at [[Exeter College, Oxford]], receiving a [[British undergraduate degree classification#First-class honours|first-class degree]] in 1948, and completed his graduate studies in the [[Early Christianity|early Church]] in 1956 under the [[patristics]] scholar [[Frank Leslie Cross]].<ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Stanley|first=Brian|date=October 2001|title=Profile of Andrew Walls|journal=Epworth Review|volume=28|issue=4|pages=16–26}}</ref>
He taught at [[Fourah Bay College]], [[Sierra Leone]] (1957–62) and the [[University of Nigeria, Nsukka]] (1962–65). He was later appointed to a post in [[Church history|ecclesiastical history]] in the [[University of Aberdeen]] in 1966, before being the first head of the Department of [[Religious studies]] in the [[University of Aberdeen]] (1970). He would subsequently move to the [[University of Edinburgh]] in 1986. He is currently Professor of the History of Mission at [[Liverpool Hope University]], Honorary Professor at the [[University of Edinburgh]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cswc.div.ed.ac.uk/people/|title=Academic Staff|publisher=University of Edinburgh|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref> Research Professor at [[Africa International University]]'s Center for World Christianity,<ref>{{cite web|title=Research Professor at the Center for World Christianity of AIU|url=http://www.negst.edu/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=292%3Aresearch-professor&catid=3%3Anewsevents|publisher=Africa International University|accessdate=14 September 2011}}</ref> and Professor Emeritus at the Akrofi-Christaller Institute of Theology, Mission and Culture.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.acighana.org/site/academics/staff.php?astaffid=7|title=Academic Staff|website=''acighana.org''|publisher=Akrofi-Christaller Institute of Theology, Mission and Culture|access-date=13 May 2016}}</ref>
Walls established the ''[[Journal of Religion in Africa]]'' in 1967 and ''[[Studies in World Christianity]]'' in 1995. He also founded the [[Centre for the Study of Christianity in the Non-Western World]] (now known as the Centre for the Study of World Christianity), first at the [[University of Aberdeen]] in 1982, before moving it to the [[University of Edinburgh]] in 1987, a year after he moved to Edinburgh.<ref>{{cite web|title=Frost's Scottish Who's Who |url=http://www.martinfrost.ws/htmlfiles/mfwhoswho/individuals/W_mfwwi/andrew_walls.html |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120516054537/http://martinfrost.ws/htmlfiles/mfwhoswho/individuals/W_mfwwi/andrew_walls.html |archivedate=16 May 2012 }}</ref>
With his late wife Doreen Harden, whom he married in 1953, they have two children, Christine and Andrew.<ref name=":1" /> After Doreen's death, he married Ingrid Reneau in 2012, a Research Fellow with the Presbyterian Mission Agency.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.presbyterianmission.org/ministries/missionconnections/reneau-ingrid/|title=Dr. Ingrid Reneau Walls|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160130135635/https://www.presbyterianmission.org/ministries/missionconnections/reneau-ingrid/|archivedate=30 January 2016|deadurl=yes}}</ref>
On 26 November 2018, Walls received an honorary degree of [[Doctor of Divinity]] from the University of Edinburgh in recognition of his scholarly contributions to the study of Christianity in Africa and the non-Western world.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ed.ac.uk/divinity/news-events/latest-news/honorary-grad-prof-andrew-walls|title=Honorary Doctor of Divinity: Professor Andrew Finlay Walls, OBE, MA, BLitt, DD, FSASco|last=|first=|date=26 November 2018|work=School of Divinity, University of Edinburgh|access-date=27 November 2018|language=en}}</ref>
==World Christianity== Walls' most significant observations have concerned the geographical trends in Christianity in the 20th and 21st centuries, especially in terms of expansion in Africa, in what is generally termed [[World Christianity]]. Historian [[Lamin Sanneh]] commented that he was 'one of the few scholars who saw that African Christianity was not just an exotic, curious phenomenon in an obscure part of the world, but that African Christianity might be the shape of things to come'.<ref name="CT">{{cite journal|last=Stafford|first=Tim|title=Historian Ahead of His Time|journal=[[Christianity Today]]|date=February 2007|url=http://www.christianitytoday.com/ct/2007/february/34.87.html|accessdate=14 September 2011}}</ref> His pioneering research led the magazine ''[[Christianity Today]]'' to describe him in 2007 as 'a historian ahead of his time' and 'the most important person you don't know'.<ref name="CT" />
Liverpool Hope University has a research centre named in honour of him, which encourages and supports research in the field of African and Asian Christianity.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.hope.ac.uk/research/researchcentres/researchcentredetails/andrewfwallscentre/|title=Andrew F. Walls Centre – Liverpool Hope University|website=hope.ac.uk|access-date=13 May 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201041011/http://www.hope.ac.uk/research/researchcentres/researchcentredetails/andrewfwallscentre/|archive-date=1 December 2017|dead-url=yes|df=dmy-all}}</ref>
==Religious studies== Although he is more well known for his work in Christianity, Walls has also been a significant pioneer in shaping the field of [[religious studies]] as it is taught in universities of Scotland.<ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Cox|first=James L.|last2=Sutcliffe|first2=Steven J.|date=March 2006|title=Religious studies in Scotland: A persistent tension with divinity|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.religion.2005.12.001|journal=Religion|volume=36|issue=1|pages=1–28|doi=10.1016/j.religion.2005.12.001}}</ref> When he first returned to Scotland, Walls taught [[Church history|Ecclesiastical History]] in the [[University of Aberdeen]] in 1966. However, he recognised that the [[Christ's College, Aberdeen|Faculty of Divinity in Aberdeen]] did not allow for a sufficient global perspective of religion, and founded the Department of [[Religious studies]] outside the Faculty of Divinity in 1970.
Significantly, Walls' work in Aberdeen would establish the first department of Religious Studies in Scotland.<ref name=":0" /> In the mid-1970s, the department would be known for emphasising work in the study of what was then called '[[Indigenous religions|primal religions]]'. Moreover, his vision for a global perspective of religion allowed for Walls to attract a number of significant members of staff and students who were interested in religions of the non-Western world. It would also be in this new department that the original [[Centre for the Study of World Christianity|Centre for the Study of Christianity in the Non-Western World]] was established, before eventually being relocated to the [[New College, Edinburgh|University of Edinburgh]] in 1987. It has been known as the Centre for the Study of World Christianity since 2009.
