{{Infobox basketball biography | name = Jim Marsh | image = Jim Marsh.png | width = 120px | caption = | number = 51 | position = [[Forward (basketball)|Forward]] | height_ft = 6 | height_in = 7 | weight_lb = 215 | league = | birth_date = {{birth date and age|1946|4|26}} | birth_place = | death_date = | death_place = | nationality = American | high_school = [[Pasadena High School (Pasadena, California)|Pasadena]] ([[Pasadena, California]]) | college = [[USC Trojans men's basketball|USC]] (1965–1968) | draft_year = 1968 | draft_round = 11 | draft_pick = 136 | draft_team = [[Seattle SuperSonics]] | career_start = 1971 | career_end = 1972 | years1 = 1971–1972 | team1 = [[Portland Trail Blazers]] | highlights = | stat1label = [[Point (basketball)|Points]] | stat1value = 119 (3.1 ppg) | stat2label = [[Rebound (basketball)|Rebounds]] | stat2value = 84 (2.2 rpg) | stat3label = [[Assist (basketball)|Assists]] | stat3value = 30 (0.8 apg) }} '''James Marsh''' (born April 26, 1946) is a retired American professional basketball player who competed in the [[National Basketball Association|NBA]] for one season. He played college basketball at the [[USC Trojans men's basketball|University of Southern California]], and played professionally for the [[Portland Trail Blazers]] of the NBA.<ref name=PBR>{{Cite web| title = Jim Marsh statistics| work = basketball-reference.com| publisher = Sports Reference, LLC| url =https://www.basketball-reference.com/players/m/marshji01.html}}</ref>
After his playing career, Marsh spent time as an assistant coach at the [[University of Utah]] before transitioning to a career as a broadcaster for the [[Seattle SuperSonics]], which is the franchise by whom he was drafted out of college. He served as the [[color commentator]] on SuperSonics television broadcasts for 12 years.<ref name=PI-WhereAreTheyNow>{{cite news |last=Raley |first=Dan |title=Where Are They Now: Jim Marsh, former USC, NBA player |url=http://www.seattlepi.com/sports/article/Where-Are-They-Now-Jim-Marsh-former-USC-NBA-1297941.php |accessdate=July 12, 2012 |newspaper=[[Seattle Post-Intelligencer]] |date=January 19, 2009 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/696ufxG6U?url=http://www.seattlepi.com/sports/article/Where-Are-They-Now-Jim-Marsh-former-USC-NBA-1297941.php |archivedate=July 12, 2012 |deadurl=no |df= }}</ref>
Marsh was diagnosed with [[Parkinson's disease]] in 2004.<ref name=SteveKelley_Parkinsons>{{cite web|last1=Kelley|first1=Steve|title=Parkinson's is no match for Marsh|url=http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20040820&slug=kell20|publisher=[[The Seattle Times]]|accessdate=February 9, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150209211101/http://community.seattletimes.nwsource.com/archive/?date=20040820&slug=kell20|archivedate=February 9, 2015}}</ref> He has two adult daughters and lives in [[Kirkland, Washington]], where he continues to coach an [[Amateur Athletic Union|AAU]] basketball team.<ref name=PI-WhereAreTheyNow/>
