'''Siculus''' (from [[Greek language|Greek]]) was a legendary king and son of [[Italus]].<ref name="MasonMason2006">{{cite book|author1=Carl Waldman, Catherine Mason|author2=Catherine Mason|title=Encyclopedia of European Peoples|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=kfv6HKXErqAC&pg=PA735|accessdate=2 December 2012|year=2006|publisher=Infobase Publishing|isbn=978-1-4381-2918-1|pages=735–}}</ref><ref name="Wiegand1936">{{cite book|author=Edna Wiegand|title=Notes on the eighth book of the Commentary of Servius on Vergil's Aeneid|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=BTbGAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=2 December 2012|year=1936|page=67|publisher=Columbia University}}</ref><ref name="Roman and European Mythologies">{{cite book|title=Roman and European Mythologies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Uf2_kHAs22sC&pg=PA56|accessdate=2 December 2012|date=15 November 1992|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-06455-0|pages=56–}}</ref>
Thucydides and other Greek historians have suggested that he was the [[legendary progenitor]] of the [[Sicels]] (or Siculi), an [[Italic peoples|Italic people]] who colonised [[Sicily]] three hundred years before the [[Ancient Greeks]] in 1050 BCE.<ref name="MasonMason2006"/> The island was originally called Sicania after a previous legendary King called Sicanus.<ref name="Wiegand1936"/>
